post_text: The CDC recently updated their guidance on the use of masks, specifically addressing the use of gaiter/buff style face coverings and masks with exhalation valves or vents. The CDC has stated that evaluation of gaiter/buff style face coverings is ongoing, and their effectiveness is unknown at this time. Furthermore, they have stated that masks with exhalation valves or vents should NOT be worn because virus particles can escape into the air through the vent/valve. Therefore, based on this guidance from the CDC, the Florida Department of Health in St. Lucie recommended that students and employees not use these types of masks while on school campuses or district office buildings. The school district is following this recommendation and no longer allowing these types of masks.

shared_text:
Palm Pointe Educational Research School At Tradition
September 4 at 10:34 AM ·

The Project Citizen National Showcase was recently held, where students from Massachusetts to Arizona tackled problems in their community. Students from Mrs. Wright’s 3rd period Civics class from last school year earned an Exceptional rating on their project, “Water We Waiting For?” Last January, Hannah Dorval, Devin Habyan, Alexia Morgan, and Caleb Chuquillanqui represented their class at the district showcase, where they presented the class project, seeking to combat the high rate of child drownings in the state of Florida by proposing changes to public policy. They were interviewed by multiple judges and answered questions about their proposed policy, which helped the project advance to the state competition. Then, over the summer, Alexia Morgan and Hannah Raymond presented the project at the state level, where they were interviewed once again and their efforts advanced the project to the National competition, earning an Exceptional rating. Congratulations to all, they worked so hard on all parts of this project. We are so proud of our rockets!

Florida Department of Transportation
August 31 at 1:00 PM ·

Do you know when to stop for a school bus? This image depicts scenarios where you must yield to a stopped school bus. Two lane roads, multi-lane roads without a dividing median, and divided roadways where you are traveling in the same direction (behind a stopped school bus) are ALL required to come to a complete stop – no passing allowed!

#BackToSchool #DriveSafe #ChildSafetyFL #BusSafety

They are one of only 24 Incubator Schools across the U.S. that have committed to an education transformation journey with Microsoft Education. They join hundreds of other Microsoft Incubator and Showcase Schools across the globe actively empowering the students of today to create the world of tomorrow. Over the course of the next year, the school community will have the opportunity to learn and develop best practices, activities and participate in events while helping transform education globally.

CONGRATULATIONS on this amazing accomplishment!

August 11 at 7:33 PM ·

Wondering when to use a mask? Wear a mask when you are in a public setting, especially when it is difficult to stay 6 feet away from others not living in your household. You should even wear a mask in a restaurant or rideshare.

However, if everyone in your household is healthy, you do not need to wear a mask at home or in your personal vehicle. For more information on COVID-19 and masks, visit: https://bit.ly/CDC-WearingMasks.

All students, regardless of which school they attend, must submit a new meal application for the 20/21 school year.

Students will no longer be automatically approved for meals at no cost.

Now is the time to apply for the 2020/2021 free and reduce meal benefit.

This must be completed prior to August 24th so that an updated meal status is on file.

The application can be found at https://foodservice.stlucie.k12.fl.us/.

Only one meal application needs to be completed per family. Questions about completing a meal application can be emailed to mealapplication@stlucieschools.org.

Don't wait! Act now!

St. Lucie Public Schools Child Nutrition Services
June 29 at 12:00 PM ·

Summer is here! Our kitchens are still committed to bringing food to the hungry children in our communities. Our Summer Program runs at the locations listed below from June 4- July 31, 2020.

Who: Our Summer Meal Program is FREE to all children 18 years and younger.

How: Children and Parents may pick up meals by car, bike, or by walking to a nearest location.

When: Beginning June 4 and running to July 31, 2020. Meals will be served Tuesdays and Thursdays. On Tuesdays, families will receive two days worth of Breakfast and Lunch meals. On Thursdays, families will receive three days worth of Breakfast and Lunch meals.

All meals will be served from 11am-1pm in the designated pickup areas.

Where: Pick up locations by zone,

Red Zone: Bayshore Elementary, Oak Hammock K8, Manatee Academy K8, Windmill Point Elementary

Blue Zone: Northport K8, Village Green Elementary

Green Zone: Weatherbee Elementary, St. Lucie Elementary, FK Sweet Elementary, Lakewood Park Elementary, Fort Pierce Westwood Elementary, C A Moore Elementary, Forest Grove Elementary.

post_text: Summer Meal Sites
shared_text:
St. Lucie Public Schools Child Nutrition Services
June 22 at 12:00 PM ·

Summer is here! Our kitchens are still committed to bringing food to the hungry children in our communities. Our Summer Program runs at the locations listed below from June 4- July 31, 2020.

Who: Our Summer Meal Program is FREE to all children 18 years and younger.

How: Children and Parents may pick up meals by car, bike, or by walking to a nearest location.

When: Beginning June 4 and running to July 31, 2020. Meals will be served Tuesdays and Thursdays. On Tuesdays, families will receive two days worth of Breakfast and Lunch meals. On Thursdays, families will receive three days worth of Breakfast and Lunch meals.

All meals will be served from 11am-1pm in the designated pickup areas.

Where: Pick up locations by zone,

Red Zone: Bayshore Elementary, Oak Hammock K8, Manatee Academy K8, Windmill Point Elementary

Blue Zone: Northport K8, Village Green Elementary

Green Zone: Weatherbee Elementary, St. Lucie Elementary, FK Sweet Elementary, Lakewood Park Elementary, Fort Pierce Westwood Elementary, C A Moore Elementary, Forest Grove Elementary.

shared_text:
City of Port St. Lucie - City Hall
June 10 at 4:00 PM ·

🇺🇸 Fulfill your patriotic duty by filling out the U.S. Census online at 2020Census.gov, or by calling 844-330-2020. 🇺🇸

As we thoughtfully look forward to rebuilding following COVID-19, we need your help.

To build a stronger Port St. Lucie, we need you to fill out the 2020 Census. The country's decision-makers rely on these results to allocate resources and funding.

Filling out the census is quick and easy. The City is hosting a Weekly Contest and you could win a $25 virtual VISA gift card, or in its Monthly Contest, you could win a pair of tickets to see Little River Band on Nov. 14, 2020, at MIDFLORIDA Event Center!

This simple, patriotic act will greatly impact the commonwealth for the next decade. Get started here: www.cityofpsl.com/census

Happening Tonight!

#SLPSPLAYSWITHLOVE

The secondary music students in SLPS and their teachers will be honoring all those who have sacrificed so much during this Covid-19 pandemic.

Tonight, May 15 at 7PM, secondary music students in St. Lucie Public Schools will be playing or singing “Lean on Me” in their yards. Step outside and see if you hear one of our students "sharing the love!"

Please let us know by using the hashtag #SLPSPLAYSWITHLOVE.

If you feel the urge to join these young musicians, please do! (If you want to practice first, we’re playing/singing in the key of Eb)

St. Lucie Public Schools: Social Emotional Learning Focus
May 6 at 10:34 AM ·

Quote of the Day

post_text:
National Nurses Week begins each year on May 6th and ends on May 12th, Florence Nightingale's birthday.

Today, May 6, 2020 is designated as National Nurses Day.

SLPS is so fortunate to have such a qualified and dedicated staff of nurses and health staff working in the Division of Student Services and ESE and in our schools. SLPS has a cooperative agreement with the St. Lucie Department of Health which provides Registered Nurses to our schools. These nurses oversee the daily operation of our school health rooms (clinics) and provide student specific training to the many School Health Paraprofessionals working under the delegation of those nurses.

Our health care staff continue to inspire us as they are always on the front line providing quality care and training for everyone. They demonstrate care and compassion and always treat everyone with dignity and grace. National Nurses week honors individuals who are known as the heart of healthcare.

Please join SLPS in thanking our health care staff who play a vital role in the health and well-being of our students.

Exciting News! 🤩 Now there are four $25 weekly winners and a monthly winner just for filling out the #2020Census. The City of Port St. Lucie is also pleased to announce the extension of the closing date, October 1, 2020.

Remember, the sooner you enter the more chances you have to win. If a contestant doesn’t win one week, they are automatically re-entered into the next week’s random drawing.

To be eligible a contestant must fill out the U.S. Census survey, either by mail or online, then email PSLCensus2020@cityofpsl.com a photo of their confirmation number and contact information. Winners will be picked weekly and announced on social media and the City’s website. Only one winner per household. Find out more at www.CityofPSL.com/Census

post_text:
Follow Five Steps to Wash Your Hands the Right Way

Washing your hands is easy, and it’s one of the most effective ways to prevent the spread of germs. Clean hands can stop germs from spreading from one person to another and throughout an entire community—from your home and workplace to childcare facilities and hospitals.
Follow these five steps every time.

1. Wet your hands with clean, running water (warm or cold), turn off the tap, and apply soap.
2. Lather your hands by rubbing them together with the soap. Lather the backs of your hands, between your fingers, and under your nails.
3. Scrub your hands for at least 20 seconds. Need a timer? Hum the “Happy Birthday” song of the "ABC" song from beginning to end twice.
4. Rinse your hands well under clean, running water.
5. Dry your hands using a clean towel or air dry them.
